E35_ICM: Manually curated edge to E3.0 dummy node. See text.
E45_Epiblast: The epiblast is well-established to emerge from the ICM. See PMID 24968703
E45_Hypoblast: The hypoblast is well-established to emerge from the ICM. See PMID 24968703
E525_Parietal_endoderm: The parietal endoderm is well-established to arise from the hypoblast. See PMID 24968703
E525_Visceral_endoderm: The visceral endoderm is well-established to arise from the hypoblast. See PMID 24968703
E525_ExE_ectoderm: Manually curated connection between E4.5 trophoectoderm dummy node and E5.25 extraembryonic ectoderm (ExE ectoderm). See text and PMID 24968703
E55_EmVE: The embryonic visceral endoderm (EmVE) is well-established to arise from the visceral endoderm. See PMID 24968703
E55_ExVE: The extraembryonic visceral endoderm (ExVE) is well-established to arise from the visceral endoderm. See PMID 24968703
E65_Primitive_Streak: The primitive streak is well-established to arise from the epiblast. See PMID 24968703
E675_Nascent_mesoderm: The nascent mesoderm is well-established to arise from the epiblast. See PMID 22170865
E7_Primitive_Streak: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.24) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E7_Haematoendothelial_prog: Hematoendothelial progenitors are well-established to arise from nascent mesoderm. See PMC5852632
E7_Mixed_mesoderm: The cell state that we annotate as mixed mesoderm, as per original study (PMID 30787436) appears to arise from nascent mesoderm.
E7_Anterior_Primitive_Streak: The anterior primitive streak is well-established to arise from the primitive streak. See PMID 10611967
E7_PGC: Primordial germ cells (PGCs) are well-established to arise at the posterior primitive streak. See PMID 23125014.
E725_Def_endoderm: The definitive endoderm is well-established to arise from the anterior primitive streak. See PMID 10611967
E725_Notochord: The notochord is well-established to arise from the anterior primitive streak. See PMC4844759
E725_Blood_prog: The cell state that we annotate as blood progenitors, as per original study (PMID 30787436) appears to arise from hematoendothelial progenitors.
E725_Mixed_mesoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.23) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E725_Somatic_mesoderm: Somatic mesoderm (tentative label; these cells called mesenchyme by PMID 30787436) appears to arise from mixed mesoderm.
E7_Parietal_endoderm: Manually curated "self" connection between E6.75 parietal trophoectoderm dummy node and E7.0 parietal endoderm. See text.
E75_Def_endoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to anterior primitive streak (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E75_Blood_prog: Self, with an additional edge back to haematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.28) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E75_Gut: Gut is well-established to arise from definitive endoderm. See PMID 10611967
E75_Rostral_neurectoderm: Rostral neuroectoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to epiblast (0.56) and primitive streak (0.43). See PMID 29109536
E75_ExE_mesoderm: ExE mesoderm appears to emerge from mixed mesoderm. Note that although this cell state is related to allantois at next timepoint, in general, distinction from other mesodermal cell populations is challenging. See PMID 22855605.
E75_Mixed_mesoderm: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.58) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E75_Somatic_mesoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to mixed mesoderm (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E75_Splanchnic_mesoderm: Splanchnic mesoderm has edges surpassing threshold back to both nascent (0.72) and mixed (0.28) mesoderm. See PMID 16304598
E75_Paraxial_mesoderm_A: Paraxial mesoderm A arises from the nascent mesoderm. Distinguished from other paraxial mesoderm cell states based on markers Tbx1, Pax3, and potentially corresponds to anterior paraxial mesoderm. See PMID 23081715, PMID 20692252
E75_Paraxial_mesoderm_B: Paraxial mesoderm B arises from the nascent mesoderm. Distinguished from other paraxial mesoderm cell states based on markers Tbx6, Dll1, and potentially corresponds to posterior paraxial mesoderm. See PMID 15986483, PMID 20692252
E75_Caudal_lateral_epiblast: Caudal lateral epiblast appears to arise from primitive streak, marked by Nkx1-2 aka Sax1. See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/045872v1.
E75_Caudal_neurectoderm: Caudal neuroectoderm appears to emerge from primitive streak. See PMID 11748135.
E75_Surface_ectoderm: Surface ectoderm appears to emerge from primitive streak. May reflect remaining cells of epiblast, as neuroectoderm, caudal lateral epiblast also have edges back to primitive streak, while epiblast associated with rostral neuroectoderm. See PMC4691128.
E775_Primitive_erythroid: Primitive erythroid cells are well-established to emerge from blood progenitors. See PMC3904103
E775_Paraxial_mesoderm_C: Paraxial mesoderm C emerges with edges back to both nascent mesoderm (0.61) and caudal lateral epiblast (0.35). See https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/045872v1
E775_Caudal_neurectoderm: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to rostral neuroectoderm (weight 0.55) that presumably reflects incomplete separation.
E775_Gut: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to gut (weight 0.62) that presumably reflects an ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation. Minor contribution (0.15) from embryonic visceral endoderm is established example of convergence.
E775_Notochord: Self, with an additional edge back to definitive endoderm (weight 0.28) that could be explained by incomplete separation. See PMC4844759 and PMID 16752393
E775_Rostral_neurectoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to epiblast (weight 0.21) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E775_Allantois: The allantois is well-established to arise from the ExE mesoderm. See PMID 22855605
E775_Endothelium: Endothelium is well-established to arise from haematoendothelial progenitors. See PMC5852632
E775_Intermediate_mesoderm: Intermediate mesoderm emerges with edges back to both nascent (0.57) and mixed (0.23) mesoderm. See PMID 29666052
E775_Paraxial_mesoderm_B: Self, with an additional edge back to nascent mesoderm (weight 0.27) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E775_Paraxial_mesoderm_A: Self, with an additional edge back to splanchnic mesoderm (weight 0.20) that could be explained by incomplete separation.
E775_Surface_ectoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to rostral neuroectoderm (weight 0.28) that may warrant further investigation.
E775_Cardiomyocytes: Cardiomyocytes are well-established to arise from the splanchnic mesoderm. See PMC5731822
E8_Allantois: Self, with an additional edge back to ExE mesoderm (weight 0.22) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E8_Primitive_erythroid: Self, with an additional edge back to blood progenitors (weight 0.23) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E8_Paraxial_mesoderm_C: Self, with an additional edge back to caudal lateral epiblast (weight 0.40) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E8_Spinal_cord: Spinal cord neurons appear to arise from caudal neuroectoderm. See PMID 9136764
E8_Def_endoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to notochord (weight 0.36) that could be explained by incomplete separation. See PMC4844759 and PMID 16752393
E8_Endothelium: Self, with an additional edge back to haematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.33) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E8_ExE_mesoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to somatic mesoderm (weight 0.23) that reflects an established relationship and could be incomplete separation.
E8_Paraxial_mesoderm_B: Self, with an additional edge back to intermediate mesoderm (weight 0.21) that could reflect incomplete separation.
E825_NMP: Neuromesodermal progenitors (NMP) appear to arise from caudal lateral epiblast (weight 0.77) and paraxial mesoderm C (weight 0.22). See PMID 26329597.
E825_Spinal_cord: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to caudal neuroectoderm (weight 0.63) that presumably reflects an ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E825_Def_endoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to gut (weight 0.21) and notochord (weight 0.23) that could be explained by incomplete separation. See PMC4844759 and PMID 16752393
E825_Endothelium: Self, with an additional edge back to haematoendothelial progenitors (weight 0.29) that reflects an established relationship and could be explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E825_Paraxial_mesoderm_B: Self, with an additional edge back to intermediate mesoderm (weight 0.23) that could reflect incomplete separation.
E825_Forebrain_Midbrain: Forebrain/midbrain appears to arise from the rostral neurectoderm. See PMID 11731459
E825_Hindbrain: Hindbrain appears to arise from the rostral neurectoderm. See PMID 11731459
E825_Neural_crest: Neural crest appears to arise from rostral neurectoderm. Note that there were three neural crest trajectories in Cao et al. (2019). This one likely corresponds to Schwann cell precursors.
E825_Somatic_mesoderm_A: Somatic mesoderm splits to two distinguishable subpopulations, termed here A & B. It remains unclear to us what these correspond to.
E825_Somatic_mesoderm_B: Somatic mesoderm splits to two distinguishable subpopulations, termed here A & B. It remains unclear to us what these correspond to.
E85_Def_endoderm: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to notochord (weight 0.54) that could reflect incomplete separation and may warrant further exploration. See PMC4844759 and PMID 16752393
E85_ExE_mesoderm: Self, with an additional edge back to intermediate mesoderm (weight 0.36) that could reflect convergence or incomplete separation
E85_Epidermis: Epidermis appears to arise from surface ectoderm. See PMID 22449491
E85_Placodal_area: Placodal area appears to arise from surface ectoderm. See PMID 12874121
E85_Keratinized_epithelium: Keratinized epithelium appears to arise from surface ectoderm. See PMID 19422428
E95_Epidermis: Self, with an additional edge back to placodal area (weight 0.22) that could reflect convergence or incomplete separation, as both emerged from surface ectoderm at E8.5.
E95_Isthmic_organizer_cells: Isthmic organizer cells emerge from the Forebrain/Midbrain. Minor contribution (weight 0.17) from hindbrain potentially not surprising, as these are expected to arise at midbrain-hindbrain boundary. See PMID 16111543
E95_Neuron_prog: Substantial contributions to neuronal progentiors from fore/midbrain, hindbrain, and spinal cord. Reasonable example of convergence. Need to clarify distinction from the cell type that we annotate as radial glial cells. See PMC6291443
E95_Wnt8b_positive_cell_prog: Wnt8b postiive progenitors, previously termed "oligodendrocyte progenitors" emerge from the Forebrain/Midbrain. Original annotation from Cao et al. (2019), which we have subsequently recognize may likely be incorrect. Renamed Wnt8b+ cells in Cao et al. (2020). See PMC5368213
E95_Retina_primordium: Retina primordium appears to emerge from the forebrain/minbrain; connection to placodal area is interesting. Concievably reflects the lens placode but this would require further investigation.
E95_Sensory_neuron: Sensory neurons appear to arise from forebrain/midbrain, hindbrain. Neural crest, but seemingly distinct in origin from other neural crest populations defined here. Annotation from one of main clusters of Cao et al. (2019) that corresponds to neural crest (PNS neuron) trajectory. See PMID 25662262. Consider renaming to PNS neurons.
E95_Hepatocytes: Hepatocytes appear to arise from gut. See PMID 10373120
E95_Foregut_Midgut_Hindgut_epithelium: Foregut/Midgut/Hindgut epithelium appaers to arise from the gut. See PMC3374328.
E95_Notoplate: Notoplate appears to arise from the hindbrain. See PMID 12835403
E95_Radial_glia: Substantial contributions to radial glia from spinal cord, hindbrain. Reasonable example of convergence. Need to clarify distinction from neuronal progenitors. See PMC6291443
E95_Intermediate_mesoderm: Self, but with higher scoring edge back to splanchnic mesoderm (weight 0.32) that could reflect convergence or poor technical separation of mesodermal subpopulations
E95_Limb_mesenchyme_prog: Limb mesenchyme appears to arise from intermediate mesoderm, with an additional contribution from paraxial mesoderm A (weight 0.28). Contribution of intermediate mesoderm is potentially unexpected and may reflect poor technical separation of mesodermal progenitors. See PMID 15328019
E95_Paraxial_mesoderm_B: Self, but with additional edge back to intermediate mesoderm (weight 0.20) that could reflect convergence or poor technical separation of mesodermal subpopulations
E95_Renal_epithelium: Renal epithelium appears to arise from the intermediate mesoderm, as expected. See PMC2677135
E95_Ependymal_cell: Ependymal cells appear to arise from neural crest. Minor contributions (close to 0.20) from Forebrain/Midbrain and Hindbrain. Association with neural crest potentially contradicts literature which suggests origins from primitive neuroectoderm and radial glial cells.
E95_Osteoblast_prog_A: Substantial contributions to a first subpopulation of osteoblast progenitors from paraxial mesoderm A and neural crest. Tentative label. See PMID 18090740
E95_Osteoblast_prog_B: Substantial contributions to a first subpopulation of osteoblast progenitors from paraxial mesoderm A and neural crest. Tentative label. See PMID 18090740
E95_Chondrocyte_prog: Chondrocyte progenitors appear to arise from paraxial mesoderm A. Minor contributions (<0.20) from splanchnic mesoderm and neural crest are expected. See PMID 22701159.
E95_Skeletal_muscle_prog: Skeletal muscle progentiors appear to arise from the paraxial mesoderm A. See PMC1571050
E95_Stromal_cells: Diffuse contributions to apparent stromal cells from paraxial mesoderm, neural crest. Tentative annotation and may reflect poor technical separation of mesodermal progenitors.
E95_Branchial_arch_epithelium: Branchial arch epithelium (aka pharyngeal arches) appear to arise from placodal area. Minor contributions (<0.20) from paraxial mesoderm and gut may be explained by derivation from all three germ layers. See PMC4199908.
E95_Olfactory_epithelium: Olfactory epithelium appears to arise from the placodal area. See PMID 19027001
E95_Otic_epithelium: Otic epithelium appears to emerge from the placodal area. See PMC4322616
E105_Megakaryocytes: Megakaryocytes appear to arise from blood progenitors
E105_White_blood_cells: White blood cells appear to arise from blood progenitors
E105_Retina_epithelium: Retinal epithelium appear to arise from branchial arch epithelium. If this is RPE, then incorrect, as that should arise from neuroepithelium. Limited number of cells which might be at risk of technical artifacts in a global embedding, and also may be why not detected at E13.5
E105_Foregut_Midgut_Hindgut_epithelium: Self, with additional edge back to branchial arch epithelium (weight 0.24) that is interesting and may warrant further investigation (e.g. endodermal contributions)
E105_Early_chondrocyte: Early chondrocytes emerges from chondrocyte progenitors
E105_Intermediate_mesoderm: Self; minor connections (<0.20) to other mesoderms likely explained by poor technical separation of mesodermal progenitors.
E105_Cholinergic_neurons: Cholinergic neurons appear to arise from neuron progenitors
E105_Granule_neurons: Granule neurons appear to arise from neuron progenitors
E105_Inhibitory_interneurons: Inhibitory interneurons appear to arise from neuron progenitors
E105_Inhibitory_neuron_prog: Inhibitory neuron progenitors appear to arise from neuron progenitors
E105_Olfactory_sensory_neuron: Olfactory sensory neurons appear to arise from sensory neurons, with an additional edge (weight 0.21) back to neuron progenitors. May warrant further investigation. See PMC3215936.
E105_Postmitotic_premature_neurons: Postmitotic premature neurons appear to arise from neuron progenitors
E105_Small_sensory_neuron: Small sensory neurons appear to arise from neuron progentiors
E105_Def_erythrocyte: Definitive erythrocytes appear to arise from primitive erythroid cells, which we know to not be the case. This ostensibly reflects an artifact caused by rapid convergence.
E105_Radial_glia: Self, with an additional edge (weight 0.36) back to spinal cord that reflects an established relationship and is likely explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E105_Myocytes: Myocytes emerge appear to arise skeletal muscle progenitors
E115_Olfactory_epithelium: Self, with additional edge back to branchial arch epithelium (0.27) that is interesting and may warrant further investigation
E115_Connective_tissue_prog: Diffuse pseudo-ancestors for connective tissue progenitors, led by chondrocyte progenitors (weight 0.31) but also including (weight < 0.20) splanchnic mesoderm, skeletal muscle progenitors, osteoblast progenitors B, limb mesenchyme progenitors
E115_Def_erythrocyte: Self, with additional edge back to primitive erythroid cells (weight 0.31), probably an artifact caused by rapid convergence as discussed above.
E115_Early_chondrocyte: Self; connection to primitive erythroid likely relates to incomplete separation after rapid convergence of transcriptional states
E115_Squamous_epithelium: Squamous epithelium appears to arise from epidermis. Note incorrectly annotated as pericardium in Cao et al. (2019), revised in Cao et al. (2020)
E115_Keratinized_epithelium: Self, with additional edge back to epidermis (0.21) that may reflect convergence or incomplete separation
E115_Wnt8b_positive_cell: Wnt8b positive cells appear to arise from Wnt8b positive cell progenitors
E115_Retina_neuron: Retinal neurons appear to arise from retinal primordium
E115_Retina_pigment_cells: Retina pigment cells appear to arise from retinal primordium
E125_Megakaryocytes: Self, with additional edge back to definitive erythrocytes (0.21) that may warrant further investigation
E125_Inhibitory_neurons: Inhibitory neurons appear to arise from inhibitory neuron progenitors
E125_Retina_epithelium: Self, with additional edge back to olfactory epithelium (weight 0.26) that reflects an established relationship and is likely explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E125_Squamous_epithelium: Self, with additional edge back to epidermis (weight 0.20) that reflects an established relationship and is likely explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E125_Excitatory_neurons: Excitatory neurons appear to arise from postmitotic premature neurons
E125_Radial_glia: Self, with additional edge back to spinal cord (weight 0.24) that reflects an established relationship and is likely explained by ongoing differentiation or incomplete separation.
E125_Oligodendrocyte_precursor: Oligodendrocyte precursors, previously called Pdgfra positive glia, appear to arise from spinal cord, with sub-threshold edge back to hindbrain (weight 0.17)
E135_Osteoblast_prog_A: Self, with additional edge back to osteoblast prog. B (weight 0.29) that might reflect convergence or incomplete separation; note subthreshold edge to limb mesenchyme
E135_Osteoblast_prog_B: Self; note subthreshold edge to limb mesenchyme
E135_Oligodendrocyte_precursor: Self, with additional edge back to radial glia (weight 0.30) that might reflect convergence and may warrant additional investigation
E135_Somatic_mesoderm_B: Self, but with additional edge back to splanchnic mesoderm (weight 0.26) that could reflect convergence or poor technical separation of mesodermal subpopulations
E135_Stromal_cells: Self, with diffuse sub-threshold edges, the strongest to an unannotated cell population
E35_Trophectoderm: Manually curated edge to E3.0 dummy node. See text.
